@NODE DeliMIDI

  DeliMIDI 1.0  -  A DeliTracker player for midi files.

  This is just something I knocked up to demonstrate the usage of the B5MIDI
playroutine from machine code.

  To install DeliMIDI, just drag and drop the DeliMIDI file into DeliTracker's
DeliPlayers directory.

  Once DeliMIDI is installed, you can listen to midifiles just by dropping
them into DeliTracker's window.  Of course, you will need to have MIDI
equipment attached to your Amiga to hear anything!

  One slight problem with this player:  The Play/Pause button doesn't work
properly - Pressing it once plays the tune, pressing it again stops it, but
pressing it a third time plays the tune from the start instead of from where it
left off.  Implementing this properly would require modifications to the
playroutine - you've got the source, if this bothers you go ahead and fix it!

@ENDNODE

@NODE SMF1to0

  The SMF1to0 converter was written because the initial version of my
playroutine didn't support Type 1 files.  Type 0 files are simpler to handle,
so take less processor time to play.

  SMF1to0 can also add a Tempo Meta event to a Type 0 or 1 file, and also add
a XG Reset SysEx event.  These are both useful when used with the MIDI export
module of Bars&Pipes Professional (V1.0e) - which can't correctly write either!

  In essence, a type 0 file contains a list of delay-event pairs, which are
sent to the serial port in linear fashion.  Type 1 files contain `several'
(30 or 40 is not uncommon) tracks which must be played `simultaneously' - i.e.
multiple streams which must be merged into a single stream of delay-event pairs.
Since playing a type 1 file involves what is basically type 1 to type 0
conversion, a great deal of processor time can be saved if a type 1 file is
preprocessed into a type 0 file.

  I have been very careful when writing this converter not to lose any
information in the conversion process - even Meta events are preserved, so
copyright messages won't go missing!  The result is that I am unable to tell
by listening to the playback whether the original type 1 file or the newly
converted type 0 file is being played!

  The source code is provided, and you may do what you like with it, as long
as you don't try to claim it as your own work.

@ENDNODE

@NODE PlayRoutine

  This is a low-overhead Standard MIDI File playroutine which directs MIDI
events to serial.device unit 0.  Both SMF Type 0 and Type 1 files are supported
though the added complexity of SMF Type 1 files means playing them takes more
processor time.  Depending on the MIDI file in question, you can drastically
reduce the processor usage by running a Type 1 MIDI file through the @{"SMF1to0" link SMF1to0}
converter and playing the resulting type 0 file instead.

  The Playroutine itself is in this directory, both as source and linkable
object files for both the large and small data models.  N.B. these have only
been tested when linked with a quick machine code hack, and C-code compiled
with VBCC - you might need to recompile for other environments.

  The object files need to be linked with Amiga.lib, but don't need any
routines out of the C lib (except geta4() in the case of the smalldata
version.)

You should include MIDI.h in your program to declare the functions and
context information.

The following Functions are provided to be called from your program:

BOOL MIDI_Setup() - returns TRUE or FALSE, depending on whether it succeeded.

void MIDI_Cleanup()

enum MIDIErrors InitMIDIFile(unsigned char *data,ULONG bpm)
  returns an errorcode (defined in MIDI.h), after `registering' the midifile
  pointed to by data.  The initial tempo is supplied in bpm.

void PlayMIDIFile(void (*SongEndHandler)()) - Starts the playback.
  The SongEndHandler is optional, and takes the form of a simple Function
  Pointer - see the @{"source of PlaySMF" link PlaySMF/Main.c/main} for an example of how to use this.

void StopMIDIFile() - halts the playback.

There are further routines in the MIDI.c file, but you shouldn't need to call
them yourself.

The MIDI.c file also declares a structure called MIDIContext.  This is declared
as external in MIDI.h, so you can READ the MIDIContext information yourself.
DO NOT write anything into the context structure, except where expressly
permitted.  The MIDIContext structure subsumes a Semaphore which is used to
arbitrate for access to the MIDI Data.
You should ObtainSemaphore(&MIDIContext.DataSemaphore); while doing anything
to the MIDIFile (like loading it, InitMIDIFile()ing it, etc.).
Although it is safe to call PlayMIDIFile() with the semaphore held, the music
won't be started until you release it.  Once the music is playing the semaphore
will be held until either the music finishes or a stop or break signal is
received.  It is ESSENTIAL that your program does not hold the DataSemaphore
while MIDI_Cleanup() is called.  This will cause a deadly embrace as the two
processes each jealously guard a semaphore which the other wants!

As an example of how easy these routines are to use, see the accompanying
@{"PlaySMF" link PlaySMF} directory.

@ENDNODE

@NODE PlaySMF

  PlaySMF is a tiny little shell utility which demonstrates the use of the
MIDI player.  @{"Main.c" link PlaySMF/Main.c/main} contains more code to handle the command-line arguments
than the actual MIDIFile.

  Usage:
  PlaySMF FileName/A,Tempo/N

  Tempo is provided in beats per minute, and will be ignored if the file to be
played contains a SetTempo Meta event.

  If PlaySMF is already playing a MIDI file when you run another copy, the
first copy will be signalled (via a rendezvous port), telling it to stop playing
and to release its resources.  Once this is done, the new copy takes over.
Basically, this means you don't have to quit PlaySMF explicitly to run it again
with a different MIDI file.  This is extremely useful when PlaySMF is used as
an external player for IBrowse or DOpus.  You can stop a MIDI file playing just
by calling PlaySMF with no arguments, although it will complain about the
missing filename!

  Expand this program as you wish - but please credit me - and please don't
charge for it!

@ENDNODE

