@NODE Intro
  When it was released in 1985 the Amiga's musical capabilities were second
to none, but 13 years later the sound chip's age shows.
  Game soundtracks have traditionally been provided as Pro-Tracker modules,
which are usually quite passable, but playing sound effects at the same
time has always been a problem; either the music was restricted to 3
channels, to leave a channel free for sound effects, or the least important
channel of the music was temporarily cut off while the sound effect played.
Neither solution is ideal, but both are still common.
  More recently programmers have experimented with realtime mixing of sound
channels, to remove the 4-channel limit.  This leads to a small but noticable
quality loss and takes a great deal of processor time.
  Another solution is to use a CD audio track for background music, leaving
all four channels free for sounds. This is only possible if nothing needs to
be loaded from the CD while the game progresses.
  Yet another solution, (probably the best compromise to date) was found in
OnEscapee, where the background music was recorded as a sound-sample, bits of
which were constantly being loaded.  This worked well, and only needed two
channels for the music, but gave less than perfect sound quality.

  So what is the poor programmer to do?

  On the PC, MIDI music has been the norm in games for quite a long time.
It has sounded crap mind you - because the sound-cards in common use have had
a rather poor FM Synthesis chip providing the sounds.  But game soundtracks
sounded better if you bought a better soundcard, so people bought better
soundcards (we ARE talking about the PC market here!) and one of these `better
soundcards' - Yamaha's DB50XG WaveBlaster card, has recently been the subject
of an Amiga hardware hack.  A WaveBlaster card can be connected to any RS232
serial port (or any port which, like the Amiga's, supports 31250 baud) with
the bare minimum of electronics, providing an Amiga with a state-of-the-art
MIDI tone module.  See Christian Buchner's WaveBlaster hack on the Aminet
for more information.

While I'm not suggesting for a moment that we now have an Amiga market equipped
with MIDI gear, there are a few `ProjectXGs' about, and General MIDI keyboards
and tone modules are becoming cheaper and more accessible by the day, so I
would argue that it is now worth supporting MIDI as an option in games, and
the routines I present in this package are designed to make this a trivial
task!

@ENDNODE

@NODE Technical

  Technical rationale:

  The following information is not of great importance, but might be of
interest.  Then again, it might bore the hell out of you.

  » The playroutine separates the Type 1 and Type 0 players because type 0 files
    are quite a bit simpler to play, and the main objective for this player was
    low-overhead.  On my 25MHz '030, XOper reports that the Type 0 player uses
    2-3% of the processor time - though I think this excludes the time used by
    the serial device to send the data.  The Type 1 player uses roughly twice
    this much processor time.  This of course is VERY dependant on the
    particular MIDI file being played!

  » Only the most common timing model is supported - the one with the MThd
    chunk containing the number of `ticks-per-quarternote'.  I have no
    information at all about other timing models, so for now they're
    unsupported.

  » The callback function pointer supplied to PlayMIDIFile is NOT a utility
    library style callback hook.  Instead it is a simple function pointer:
    PlayMIDIFile(&MySongEndHandler); should work fine.  The handler itself can
    either call PlayMIDIFile() again, signal the parent task (hence the presence
    of the MIDIContext.ParentTask field) or even load in and register a new file
    before calling PlayMIDIFile() again.  It is perfectly acceptable to ignore
    songends by proving a NULL handler pointer.
    The simplest example of a SongEndHandler is probably this:

    void MinimalSongEndHandler()
    {
      Signal(MIDIContext.ParentTask,SIGBREAKF_CTRL_C);
    }

    (Please Note:  The handler routine will probably need to be `in scope' at
    the point of the PlayMIDIFile() call.  This basically means the handler
    routine, or at least a prototype declaration of it, will have to appear
    somewhere _before_ the PlayMIDIFile() call in your program.  Normally, you
    just need to put something like:
    void MinimalSongEndHandler();   with your global declarations.)

    An assembly language SongEndHandler should be fine as long as the usual
    register preservation rules are followed.

  » A SubTask is spawned to handle the actual playing.  Due to the timing
    resolution required, it is not appropriate to set up a simple CIA interrupt
    routine, as is usual for Protracker playroutines.  PT players generally
    use an interrupt frequency of around 50 Hz - a rate originally chosen so
    it could be tied to the VBlank interrupt - but an analogous interrupt for
    MIDI files could conceivably require a frequency of 800 Hz or more.  For
    this reason, the Delta-time until the next event is converted into an
    absolute EClockVal, and waited for using the WAITECLOCK unit of
    timer.device.  This might sound like an over-complicated method, but it
    works well, and doesn't lose time under heavy multitasking.

  » The subtask contains a geta4() call, which with VBCC is needed (when using
    the Small Data Model) to make the global variables visible to the subtask.
    In the extremely unlikely event of your compiler not having an equivalent
    mechanism, you can safely comment-out and ignore it *PROVIDED* you then use
    the `LARGE DATA MODEL' (usually selectable as a compiler option).
    If you get this wrong, you'll soon know - there's no way A4 will point to
    the Small-Data base `by accident'!

  » Warning:  The Playroutine will hike its priority to 21 shortly after
    PlayMIDIFile() has been called.  Bear this in mind if your program depends
    on a precarious balance of priorities!  Also, any intensive tasks which run
    at a priority greater than 20 will seriously screw up the music's timing.

@ENDNODE


